These are your memory: {"type": "action_response", "result": "### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe problem revolves around memory-efficient fine-tuning of pre-trained large language models (LLMs) in natural language processing (NLP). Traditional first-order (FO) optimizers like SGD and Adam require significant memory for back-propagation (BP), which is not feasible for very large models like OPT-13B.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- **Zeroth-Order (ZO) Optimization:** Proposed by Malladi et al. (2023) to replace BP with a BP-free method, specifically using ZO stochastic gradient descent (ZO-SGD) to approximate the gradient using finite differences.\n- **Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT):** Involves inserting trainable adapters between layers of the pre-trained model to reduce the number of parameters that need to be fine-tuned.\n- **Forward Gradient (Forward-Grad):** Another BP-free method that uses forward mode automatic differentiation (AD) to estimate gradients without backward evaluation.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- **Comparison and Evaluation:** There is a need for a comprehensive comparison between different ZO methods and the newly introduced Forward-Grad to understand their relative performance and efficiency.\n- **Scalability:** The scalability of these methods to even larger models and more complex tasks needs to be explored.\n- **Integration with PEFT:** Investigating how these BP-free methods can be integrated with PEFT strategies to further enhance memory efficiency.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Comparative Analysis:** Conduct a detailed comparative study of ZO-SGD, Forward-Grad, and other ZO methods in the context of LLM fine-tuning.\n2. **Scalability Testing:** Test the scalability of these methods on larger models and more complex tasks to understand their limitations and potential.\n3. **Integration with PEFT:** Explore how these BP-free methods can be combined with PEFT strategies to achieve even greater memory efficiency.\n4. **Theoretical Insights:** Develop theoretical insights into the convergence properties and efficiency of these methods, particularly in the context of LLMs.\n5. **Practical Applications:** Investigate practical applications of these methods in real-world scenarios, such as on-device training and other memory-constrained environments.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe research should focus on comparing and evaluating different BP-free optimization methods (ZO-SGD, Forward-Grad, etc.) for LLM fine-tuning, exploring their scalability, and investigating how they can be integrated with PEFT strategies. The goal is to provide a comprehensive understanding of these methods and their potential applications in memory-efficient LLM fine-tuning.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nMemory-efficient optimization techniques are crucial for the fine-tuning of large language models (LLMs) in natural language processing (NLP). Traditional first-order (FO) optimizers require significant memory for back-propagation, which is not feasible for very large models. Zeroth-order (ZO) optimization and forward gradient methods offer promising alternatives by eliminating the need for back-propagation, but their relative performance and scalability need to be thoroughly evaluated.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nWhat are the relative performance and scalability of different BP-free optimization methods (ZO-SGD, Forward-Grad, etc.) for fine-tuning large language models (LLMs)?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nSolving this problem is crucial for advancing memory-efficient fine-tuning of LLMs, which is essential for practical applications such as on-device training. This research will provide a comprehensive understanding of BP-free methods and their potential to reduce memory consumption in LLM fine-tuning, leading to more efficient and scalable NLP models.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nEvaluating the performance and scalability of BP-free methods involves addressing challenges such as ensuring unbiased gradient estimation, maintaining convergence rates, and adapting these methods to the specific requirements of LLMs. Naive approaches may fail to capture the nuances of these methods, and technical obstacles include the need for rigorous numerical experiments and the integration of these methods with existing PEFT strategies.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on individual BP-free methods without a comprehensive comparison. The scalability and integration with PEFT strategies have not been thoroughly explored. This research aims to fill these gaps by providing a detailed analysis and evaluation of these methods.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology involves conducting a comparative study of ZO-SGD, Forward-Grad, and other ZO methods using a variety of LLMs and tasks. The study will include rigorous numerical experiments to evaluate performance and scalability. The results will provide insights into the relative strengths and weaknesses of these methods and their potential for integration with PEFT strategies. Expected outcomes include a comprehensive understanding of BP-free methods and their application in memory-efficient LLM fine-tuning."}

