n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nEvaluating the performance and scalability of BP-free methods involves addressing challenges such as ensuring unbiased gradient estimation, maintaining convergence rates, and adapting these methods to the specific requirements of LLMs. Naive approaches may fail to capture the nuances of these methods, and technical obstacles include the need for rigorous numerical experiments and the integration of these methods with existing PEFT strategies.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on individual BP-free methods without a comprehensive comparison. The scalability and integration with PEFT strategies have not been thoroughly explored. This research aims to fill these gaps by providing a detailed analysis and evaluation of these methods.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology involves conducting a comparative study of ZO-SGD, Forward-Grad, and other ZO methods using a variety of LLMs and tasks. The study will include rigorous numerical experiments to evaluate performance and scalability. The results will provide insights into the relative strengths and weaknesses of these methods and their potential for integration with PEFT strategies. Expected outcomes include a comprehensive understanding of BP-free methods and their application in memory-efficient LLM fine-tuning."} {"type": "action_response", "result": "To systematically refine the research proposal, I will follow the outlined tasks step-by-step. Here is the detailed plan and execution:\n\n### Step 1: Refine Research Questions\n\n**Current Research Questions:**\n1. What is the problem?\n2. Why is it interesting and important?\n3. Why is it hard?\n4. Why hasn't it been solved before?\n5. What are the key components of my approach and results?\n\n**Refined Research Questions:**\n1. **What are the relative performance and scalability of different BP-free optimization methods (ZO-SGD, Forward-Grad, etc.) for fine-tuning large language models (LLMs)?**\n2. **How can BP-free methods be integrated with Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT) strategies to enhance memory efficiency in LLM fine-tuning?**\n3. **What are the theoretical convergence properties of BP-free methods in the context of LLMs, and how do they compare to traditional first-order methods?**\n4. **What are the practical applications of BP-free methods in real-world scenarios, such as on-device training and other memory-constrained environments?**\n5. **What are the key technical challenges in adapting BP-free methods to the specific requirements of LLMs, and how can these challenges be addressed?**\n\n### Step 2: Enhance Methodology\n\n**Experimental Setup:**\n- **LLMs:** Use a variety of LLMs, including OPT-13B, GPT-3, and BERT, to ensure generalizability.\n- **Datasets:** Utilize standard NLP datasets such as GLUE, SQuAD, and IMDb Reviews.\n- **Tasks:** Include tasks like text classification, question answering, and sentiment analysis.\n\n**Evaluation Metrics:**\n- **Performance Metrics:** Accuracy, F1-score, and perplexity.\n- **Scalability Metrics:** Memory usage, training time, and computational efficiency.\n- **Convergence Metrics:** Convergence rate and stability of the optimization process.\n\n**Comparative Study:**\n- Conduct a comparative study of ZO-SGD, Forward-Grad, and other ZO methods.\n- Evaluate each method on the selected LLMs, datasets, and tasks.\n- Integrate BP-free methods with PEFT strategies and evaluate the combined performance.\n\n### Step 3: Clarify Expected Outcomes\n\n**Specific Outcomes:**\n1. **Identify the most effective BP-free method for LLM fine-tuning.**\n2. **Understand the scalability of BP-free methods across different LLMs and tasks.**\n3. **Explore the integration of BP-free methods with PEFT strategies to enhance memory efficiency.**\n4. **Provide theoretical insights into the convergence properties of BP-free methods in the context of LLMs.**\n5. **Demonstrate practical applications of BP-free methods in real-world scenarios, such as on-device training.**\n\n### Step 4: Literature Review\n\n**Key Areas to Review:**\n- **Zeroth-Order Optimization:** Focus on ZO-SGD and other ZO methods.\n- **Forward Gradient Methods:** Explore Forward-Grad and similar techniques.\n- **Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT):** Review existing PEFT strategies and their integration with optimization methods.\n- **Large Language Models (LLMs):** Understand the architecture and requirements of LLMs.\n- **Memory-Efficient Optimization:** Investigate existing approaches and their limitations.\n\n### Step 5: Preliminary Experiments\n\n**Plan:**\n- Conduct preliminary experiments to validate the feasibility of the proposed methodology.\n- Use a smaller subset of the selected LLMs, datasets, and tasks.\n- Evaluate the performance and scalability of BP-free methods and their integration with PEFT strategies.\n\n**Expected Results:**\n- Validate the effectiveness of BP-free methods.\n- Identify any potential issues or challenges.\n- Refine the methodology based on preliminary results.\n\n### Step 6: Draft the Proposal\n\n**Structure:**\n1. **Introduction:** Provide background, problem statement, and research significance.\n2. **Literature Review:** Summarize existing research and identify gaps.\n3. **Research Questions:** Clearly state the refined research questions.\n4. **Methodology:** Detail the experimental setup, evaluation metrics, and comparative study.\n5. **Expected Outcomes:** Define specific, achievable outcomes.\n6. **Preliminary Results:** Present findings from preliminary experiments.\n7. **Conclusion:** Summarize the research proposal and its potential impact.\n\n**Content:**\n- Ensure the proposal is well-structured and clearly communicates the significance and feasibility of the research.\n- Include visual aids, tables, and figures to enhance clarity.\n\nBy following this plan, I can systematically refine and develop a comprehensive research proposal that addresses the key aspects of the research idea."}

