s with PEFT strategies and evaluate the combined performance.\n\n### Step 3: Clarify Expected Outcomes\n\n**Specific Outcomes:**\n1. **Identify the most effective BP-free method for LLM fine-tuning.**\n2. **Understand the scalability of BP-free methods across different LLMs and tasks.**\n3. **Explore the integration of BP-free methods with PEFT strategies to enhance memory efficiency.**\n4. **Provide theoretical insights into the convergence properties of BP-free methods in the context of LLMs.**\n5. **Demonstrate practical applications of BP-free methods in real-world scenarios, such as on-device training.**\n\n### Step 4: Literature Review\n\n**Key Areas to Review:**\n- **Zeroth-Order Optimization:** Focus on ZO-SGD and other ZO methods.\n- **Forward Gradient Methods:** Explore Forward-Grad and similar techniques.\n- **Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT):** Review existing PEFT strategies and their integration with optimization methods.\n- **Large Language Models (LLMs):** Understand the architecture and requirements of LLMs.\n- **Memory-Efficient Optimization:** Investigate existing approaches and their limitations.\n\n### Step 5: Preliminary Experiments\n\n**Plan:**\n- Conduct preliminary experiments to validate the feasibility of the proposed methodology.\n- Use a smaller subset of the selected LLMs, datasets, and tasks.\n- Evaluate the performance and scalability of BP-free methods and their integration with PEFT strategies.\n\n**Expected Results:**\n- Validate the effectiveness of BP-free methods.\n- Identify any potential issues or challenges.\n- Refine the methodology based on preliminary results.\n\n### Step 6: Draft the Proposal\n\n**Structure:**\n1. **Introduction:** Provide background, problem statement, and research significance.\n2. **Literature Review:** Summarize existing research and identify gaps.\n3. **Research Questions:** Clearly state the refined research questions.\n4. **Methodology:** Detail the experimental setup, evaluation metrics, and